## Coding Standards

### Naming Conventions

- **Component files**: `PascalCase` — `AppointmentCard.tsx`, `BookingForm.tsx`
- **Hook files**: `camelCase` prefixed with `use` — `useAppointments.ts`, `useAuthUser.ts`
- **Utility / service files**: `camelCase` — `appointmentApi.ts`, `formatDate.ts`
- **Type / interface names**: `PascalCase` — `Appointment`, `BookingFormValues`
- **CSS classes**: Tailwind utilities only — no custom class names except in `styles/` globals
- **Variables / functions**: `camelCase` — `patientId`, `handleSubmit`, `fetchAppointments`
- **Constants**: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` — `MAX_PAGE_SIZE`, `API_BASE_URL`

All identifiers, comments, and error messages must be in English.

### Component Conventions

#### Functional Components Only

All components are function components. No class components.

```tsx
// Good
type AppointmentCardProps = {
  appointment: Appointment;
  onCancel: (id: string) => void;
};

export function AppointmentCard({ appointment, onCancel }: AppointmentCardProps) {
  return (
    <div className="rounded-lg border p-4 shadow-sm">
      <p className="text-sm text-gray-500">{appointment.scheduledAt}</p>
      <button
        type="button"
        className="mt-2 text-red-500 hover:underline"
        onClick={() => onCancel(appointment.id)}
      >
        Cancel
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

#### Props

- Always define props as a named `type` (not `interface`) for consistency.
- Use destructuring in function signature.
- Avoid prop drilling beyond 2 levels — use Context or co-locate state.

#### Component Size

- A component should do one thing. Extract sub-components when JSX exceeds ~80 lines.
- Keep page components thin — they compose features, they do not contain business logic.

